---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import FirstFixTimeline from '@/components/react/FirstFixTimeline.tsx';
import DsmReassembly from '@/components/react/DsmReassembly.tsx';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { INAV_WORDS } from '@/data/inav-words';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="From signal to first authenticated fix"
  description="How a receiver collects I/NAV words and OSNMA material to reach a first authenticated position fix."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="5 · The receiver"
    title="From signal to first authenticated fix"
    lead="A position fix needs navigation data; an authenticated fix needs that data plus the OSNMA tag and the key that signs it — and the key arrives later. Here is the whole journey."
  />

  <p>
    The Galileo navigation message is not one packet but a stream of
    <strong>word types</strong>, each carrying a piece of what a receiver needs.
    A 30-second subframe is 15 pages, and those pages carry the words in sequence.
    To compute a position for one satellite, the receiver must collect its
    ephemeris, clock and health — word types 1 to 5 — plus time.
  </p>

  <h2>The words a fix needs</h2>
  <div class="not-prose my-5 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-line bg-panel/50">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
      <thead>
        <tr class="text-left text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-muted">
          <th class="border-b border-line px-3 py-2">Word</th>
          <th class="border-b border-line px-3 py-2">Carries</th>
          <th class="border-b border-line px-3 py-2">For fix?</th>
          <th class="border-b border-line px-3 py-2">OSNMA</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          INAV_WORDS.map((w) => (
            <tr class="border-b border-line/60 last:border-0">
              <td class="px-3 py-2 font-mono font-medium text-brand-bright">{w.wt}</td>
              <td class="px-3 py-2 text-ink/90">{w.carries}</td>
              <td class="px-3 py-2">{w.neededForFix ? <span class="text-ok">required</span> : <span class="text-muted">—</span>}</td>
              <td class="px-3 py-2">{w.adkd !== undefined ? <span class="font-mono text-tag">ADKD {w.adkd}</span> : <span class="text-muted">—</span>}</td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>
    OSNMA tags of type <strong>ADKD = 0</strong> authenticate word types 1-5 — exactly
    the ephemeris and clock a fix relies on <DocRef doc="icd" section="4.2.1.3" />.
  </p>

  <h2>Power-on to authenticated fix</h2>
  <p>
    Play the journey. Notice the gap between the plain fix (TTFF) and the
    authenticated fix (TTFAF): it exists because the key that validates the tags is
    only disclosed in the following subframe.
  </p>

  <FirstFixTimeline client:visible />

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      A receiver can output a position at TTFF and then <em>upgrade</em> it to
      "authenticated" a little later, once the key arrives and the tags check out.
      Many receivers flag each fix with its authentication state.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Reassembling a DSM from many satellites</h2>
  <p>
    Before any of this, the receiver needs the signed KROOT — and that arrives in
    pieces. A DSM-KROOT is split into blocks carried one per subframe in the slow
    HKROOT stream. Because OSNMA data is common to the whole constellation, those
    blocks can come from <strong>different satellites</strong>, out of order and with
    duplicates. The receiver just collects them until the message is complete
    <DocRef doc="rxg" section="3.3" />:
  </p>

  <DsmReassembly client:visible />

  <Callout type="tip">
    <p>
      This redundancy is a feature: the receiver does not depend on any single
      satellite staying in view. It gathers whatever OSNMA blocks it can hear and
      reassembles the same DSM from the constellation.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
